# UI System (Architecture Contract)

This file defines the global UI architecture rules. It is strictly limited to:
- layer definition
- composition model
- UI responsibility separation

It does NOT define:
- styling values (see design-tokens.mdc)
- dependency rules (see ui-boundaries.mdc)

---

# 1. UI Layer Model

The system is strictly layered:

## 1. Primitives Layer (shadcn/ui)
- Base UI components (Button, Input, Card, Dialog, etc.)
- Stateless UI primitives
- Must remain framework-agnostic in behavior
- No business logic allowed
- No feature awareness allowed

Rule:
- Primitives are the foundation of the system and must not be reimplemented

---

## 2. Shared UI Layer (shared/ui)
- Reusable, domain-agnostic UI components
- Built only from primitives
- Example: FormField, ModalWrapper, EmptyState, DataTable base
- Must not contain business logic or domain rules

Rule:
- Shared UI is system-level abstraction only

---

## 3. Feature UI Layer (features/*)
- Business-specific UI composition
- Built from shared/ui + primitives
- May contain local state and domain logic
- Represents product behavior and feature-specific UI

Rule:
- Feature UI is composition, not foundation

---

## 4. Layout Layer (layouts/pages)
- Structural composition only
- Defines page structure, spacing layout, and UI organization
- Must not contain business logic
- Must not define reusable UI primitives

Rule:
- Layouts define structure only, never behavior

---

# 2. Composition Model

UI must follow strict composition rules:

- UI is assembled, not duplicated
- Prefer extending existing components over creating new ones
- Small variations must be handled via composition or variants (cva)
- Wrapping is preferred over forking or copying

Hard rule:
- No duplicated UI components with minor differences

---

# 3. Responsibility Principle

Each UI responsibility must exist in exactly one layer:

- primitives define base behavior
- shared/ui defines reusable system abstractions
- features define business-specific composition
- layouts define structure only

Rule:
- No layer is allowed to redefine responsibilities of another

---

# 4. Component Creation Rule

When creating UI:

1. Check primitives first
2. Check shared/ui second
3. Only then create feature-specific UI
4. Avoid creating new components without verifying reuse potential

Rule:
- Creation requires justification over reuse

---

# 5. Anti-Fragmentation Principle

- No parallel implementations of the same UI concept
- If a component is ≥80% similar to an existing one → reuse or extend it
- UI divergence across features is forbidden

Rule:
- Consistency is a system constraint, not a preference

---

# 6. State vs UI Separation

- UI components should remain deterministic when possible
- Business logic belongs exclusively in feature layer
- Layouts must not contain domain state or behavior

Rule:
- Side effects in UI are exceptional, not default behavior

---

# 7. System Philosophy

This system enforces:

- strict UI layering
- compositional architecture over duplication
- predictable UI structure across the application
- long-term maintainability of UI systems